<span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; ">I while back I bought a Sigma Micro USB <a class="zem_slink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Webcam" title="Webcam" rel="wikipedia">webcam</a>. These little guys will run you about $5 with overseas shipping included. They're supported by the</span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; "><a href="http://linux-uvc.berlios.de/">&nbsp;UVC-Video</a></span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; ">&nbsp;</span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; ">drivers in linux, but until recently, <a class="zem_slink" href="http://opencv.willowgarage.com/wiki/" title="OpenCV" rel="homepage">OpenCV</a> didn't support their output format. But with OpenCV 1.1, all that is fixed. The standard webcam interfaces work great with this camera, and I've started playing with some <a class="zem_slink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corner_detection" title="Corner detection" rel="wikipedia">corner detection</a> on it.</span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; "><br /></span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; "><br /></span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; ">However, there are a few catches:</span><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; "><br /></span><ul style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; "><li>Don't expect to get more than a few <a class="zem_slink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frame_rate" title="Frame rate" rel="wikipedia">frames per second</a> right now. With no processing, I get 6fps.</li><li>Linux can only drive the camera at 640x480 for right now</li><li>The Auto White Balacing is terrible.</li></ul><span class="Apple-style-span" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: 'Times New Roman'; font-size: medium; ">All-in-all, probably worth about five dollars. At least it allows you to do basic opencv camera work.</span>
